          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="mistake-item">
          <span class="mistake-icon">✗</span>
          <div>
            <strong>Unclear maintenance responsibilities:</strong> Who pays for what
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Visa and Residence Connection</h3>
      <p>Your tenancy contract is one proof of address for residence visa purposes. While Emirates ID and utility bills are often preferred, some PRO officers request an Arabic lease. If you are sponsoring family members, having a translated lease ready can speed up the process.</p>

      <p>The lease also proves you have adequate housing for dependent visas. The minimum space requirements vary by emirate and visa type. The translation should clearly show the property size and bedroom count.</p>

      <h3>Free Zone and DIFC Leases</h3>
      <p>Free zone accommodations and DIFC-located offices have their own lease formats:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>DIFC:</strong> Common law jurisdiction, English-language contracts standard</li>
        <li><strong>JAFZA/DAFZA:</strong> Free zone standard templates</li>
        <li><strong>Staff accommodation:</strong> Special regulations apply</li>
      </ul>

      <p>For disputes involving free zone properties, you may still need Arabic translation if the case goes to mainland courts rather than free zone tribunals.</p>

      <h3>Security Deposit Disputes</h3>
      <p>Security deposit claims are among the most common RDSC cases. The translation of deposit clauses requires precision on three points:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Deposit amount and currency:</strong> Must match the original exactly (AED amounts, cheque numbers)</li>
        <li><strong>Return conditions:</strong> "Normal wear and tear" has specific Arabic legal equivalents. Translating this incorrectly can change what deductions are allowed</li>
        <li><strong>Timeline for return:</strong> If the lease specifies days, the translation must use days — not approximate equivalents like "within a month"</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Landlords sometimes deduct from deposits citing damage not covered by the Arabic version of the contract. Having an accurate translation of the deposit clause protects both parties.</p>

      <h3>RERA Rent Calculator and Escalation Clauses</h3>
      <p>Dubai's RERA Rent Calculator determines the maximum allowable rent increase based on how far below market rate a property is. Lease translations must accurately render escalation language:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>"Per RERA index"</strong> — references the official calculator, limiting increases to 0-20% depending on current vs. market rent</li>
        <li><strong>"Mutually agreed"</strong> — gives both parties negotiation room, but must be translated as bilateral agreement, not unilateral landlord right</li>
        <li><strong>Fixed percentage</strong> — some leases specify a flat rate increase (e.g., 5% annually). The Arabic translation must preserve this as an exact figure</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Ambiguous escalation translations are a frequent source of RDSC disputes. We translate escalation clauses with reference to the specific RERA terminology used in tribunal decisions.</p>

      <h3>Early Termination and Buyout Clauses</h3>
      <p>Tenants breaking a lease early face penalties. Commercial leases often have complex exit calculations. Translation must capture:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Penalty amount or formula (remaining rent, fixed sum, or sliding scale)</li>
        <li>Notice period for early exit (distinct from standard termination notice)</li>
        <li>Conditions that waive the penalty (relocation, force majeure)</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Realistic Timeline</h3>
      <p>Standard residential leases (4-8 pages) translate in 4-6 hours. Commercial leases with multiple annexes take 24 hours. If you have an RDSC hearing date, tell us when you upload. We prioritize based on court deadlines.</p>

      <div class="info-callout">
